"1171–1250":"1171–1250","1180–1269":"1180–1269","before 1225":"før 1225","before 1203":"før 1203","1250":"1250","1171":"1171","1180":"1180","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1266":"1266","1200":"1200","about 1203":"omkring 1203","about 1225":"omkring 1225","Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England","Wentworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth, Jórvík, England","Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth Woodhouse, Jórvík, England","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"about 1203–1238":"circa 1203–1238","1203–1238":"1203–1238","1200–Female":"1200–Overleden","1225–1266":"1225–1266","1171–1250":"1171–1250","1180–1269":"1180–1269","before 1225":"vóór 1225","before 1203":"vóór 1203","1250":"1250","1171":"1171","1180":"1180","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1266":"1266","1200":"1200","about 1203":"circa 1203","about 1225":"circa 1225","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wentworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth, Yorkshire, England","Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1203–1238":"about 1203–1238","1203–1238":"1203–1238","1200–Female":"1200–Deceased","1225–1266":"1225–1266","1171–1250":"1171–1250","1180–1269":"1180–1269","before 1225":"before 1225","before 1203":"before 1203","1250":"1250","1171":"1171","1180":"1180","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1266":"1266","1200":"1200","about 1203":"about 1203","about 1225":"about 1225","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wentworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth, Yorkshire, England","Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Woodhouse","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from any of various places (in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Yorkshire, Northumberland, Shropshire, and elsewhere) called Woodhouse, or a topographic name for someone who lived at a ‘house in the wood’ (Middle English <i>wode</i>, <i>hous</i>, Old English <i>wudu</i>, <i>hūs</i>).","variant of   Woodiwiss  , from Middle English <i>wodewose</i>, which by the 16th century was sometimes written as <i>wodowes</i>, <i>woodose</i>, and <i>wodehouse</i>. The confusion with <i>woodhouse</i> probably arose because both words (and both names) were pronounced /wudus/ or /wudǝs/ in local dialect.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Woodis","meanings":["English:","perhaps a nickname from Old English <i>wuduwāsa</i>‘faun, satyr’.","alternatively, a shortened form of   Woodhouse  ."]},{"name":"Woodiwiss","meanings":["English (mainly Derbyshire and Yorkshire): nickname from Middle English <i>wodewose</i>, <i>wodewese</i> (Old English <i>wudewāse</i>) ‘wild man of the woods’. This word was also used to denote a person dressed to represent such a being in a play or pageant. Wodewoses (male and female) were mythical creatures of English and ancient Germanic folklore, akin to the fauns and satyrs of Classical mythology. The surname may also have been acquired by someone who lived and worked in the woods or perhaps by an unusually hairy man."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":12,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":21,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Woodhouse was born about 1203, in Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England, his father, William Woodhouse, was 34 and his mother, Anne Reppes, was 11201. He married Mrs William Wodehouse before 1225, in Wentworth, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1238, in Barnsley, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 36."},"et":{"about 1203–1238":"umbes 1203–1238","1203–1238":"1203–1238","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1225–1266":"1225–1266","1171–1250":"1171–1250","1180–1269":"1180–1269","before 1225":"enne 1225","before 1203":"enne 1203","1250":"1250","1171":"1171","1180":"1180","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1266":"1266","1200":"1200","about 1203":"umbes 1203","about 1225":"umbes 1225","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wentworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth, Yorkshire, England","Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England"